{"id":"ev_4591e45b2186417f","runId":"run_279","type":"delegation","at":1782654253441,"data":{"workItemId":"wi_0654168a0b31431d","atom":0,"task":"Build a READ-ONLY live observation harness so the founder can observe the one real live-daemon-boot retention GC pass that is this priority's archive gate. The engine is already built and proven on a COPY of live data by scripts/proof-retention-integration.mjs; do NOT duplicate that. This new script measures the REAL install around the founder's manual daemon Refresh and never mutates it.\n\nFILE: scripts/observe-retention-live.mjs (Node ESM, runnable as `node scripts/observe-retention-live.mjs ...`, matching the style/header conventions of scripts/proof-retention-integration.mjs).\n\nBEHAVIOR — two snapshot modes plus a diff:\n- `--snapshot <before|after> --out <path>`: capture a JSON snapshot of the live install and write it to <path>. The snapshot MUST include: (a) total `local/` footprint bytes and the sizes of local/cocoder.db, local/cocoder.db-wal, local/oz-audit.log; (b) local/runs run-dir count total and per-workspace (reuse the nested <workspaceId>/<runId> walk like proof-retention-integration.mjs countRunDirs); (c) from a READ-ONLY open of the run store (openRunStore on local/cocoder.db): total run rows, run rows per workspace, and the explicit set of NON-TERMINAL / protected run ids and their statuses (running, awaiting-founder, awaiting-archive-confirmation, held) — these are the runs that must survive the GC pass; (d) a snapshot timestamp passed in or read from the filesystem (do NOT call Date.now()/new Date() in a way that breaks determinism is not required here — a normal timestamp is fine for an operational script).\n- `--diff --before <path> --after <path>`: load both snapshots and PRINT + ASSERT the live-effectiveness verdict: footprint delta (db/wal/audit/runDirs before vs after), that EVERY non-terminal/protected run id present in the BEFORE snapshot is STILL PRESENT in the AFTER snapshot's store rows and run dirs (fail loudly if any protected run was pruned), and that the audit log contains the retention GC entry written by the pass (grep local/oz-audit.log for the GC marker the engine emits — inspect packages/.../retention-gc.ts to find the exact audit entry shape/type and match on it; do not invent a marker). Exit non-zero with a clear FAIL line if any invariant is violated; exit 0 with a human-readable PASS summary otherwise.\n\nHARD SAFETY REQUIREMENTS:\n- The script is strictly READ-ONLY against the live install: it opens the store read-only and only stat()s / reads files and the audit log. It MUST NOT write to, delete from, or flip any flag in local/ (it never edits settings.json, never calls runRetentionGcOnce, never checkpoints WAL). The actual GC is performed by the real daemon at boot; this script only observes.\n- Resolve the install root (cocoderHome / local/) the same way the daemon/proof scripts do; do not hardcode an absolute path.\n- If you add any unit test, it must be fixture-only and never touch real install paths (standards). A heavy test is not required; the script's own acceptance run is the proof.\n\nACCEPTANCE (run these yourself and capture output):\n1. `node scripts/observe-retention-live.mjs --snapshot before --out /tmp/reten-before.json` exits 0, writes a well-formed JSON snapshot containing footprint + runDirs + protected-run set, and provably mutates nothing under local/ (e.g. compare `du -s local` or a couple of mtimes before/after the snapshot run).\n2. `node scripts/observe-retention-live.mjs --diff --before /tmp/reten-before.json --after /tmp/reten-before.json` (same file as both args) exits 0 and prints a PASS summary with zero footprint delta and all protected runs intact — proving the diff/assertion logic is sound on a no-op.\n3. Typecheck/lint clean for the new file per repo tooling.\n\nWHAT MUST NOT BREAK: no change to any engine file (retention*.ts, store, run-dir, daemon launcher), no change to settings, no new runtime wiring — this is a standalone operational observe script only. Report the exact commands you ran and their output as evidence."}}
